---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Best Sellers — Myprotein Brand Hub PLP">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: Best Sellers</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein Brand Hub Listing Page &mdash; Audited 4 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      This audit covers the Brand Hub Best Sellers page at <code>/c/brandhub/best-sellers/</code>,
      which surfaces 133 products across a 4-column grid. The page's core proposition — community-validated
      picks — is almost entirely absent from the product cards themselves. There are no ratings, no rank
      indicators, and no social proof on individual items to justify why each product belongs here.
      Combined with a category mix spanning running shoes (£165), supplement bars (£19.99), and knee
      sleeves (£74.99) with no structural separation, users land on a page that looks and behaves like
      a generic PLP rather than a curated bestseller destination. The QUICK BUY CTA is also missing the
      brand signature mint ring, and with no visible load-more or pagination for the remaining 75 products,
      a large portion of the catalogue is effectively unreachable.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="No ratings or social proof on product cards"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="no-ratings-on-cards"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Product cards on the Best Sellers grid display no star ratings, review counts, or any social
        proof indicator. DOM inspection confirms no <code>[class*="rating"]</code> or
        <code>[class*="star"]</code> elements exist within the card structure. The page headline
        copy reads: <em>"Put your trust in the community. These picks are all bestsellers for nutrition,
        accessories, and apparel made to move with you"</em> — yet the cards provide no evidence of that
        community validation.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-best-sellers-2026-06-04/product-grid-desktop.png" alt="Product grid showing cards with no ratings" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        On a page whose value proposition is community-driven popularity, the absence of ratings is a
        direct contradiction. Users expect bestseller lists to be backed by visible social proof —
        without it, the curation feels arbitrary. Ratings are one of the most well-evidenced CRO
        levers in ecommerce; their absence on the card most likely reduces click-through and add-to-bag
        rates versus pages where they are shown.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Render the average star rating and review count on each product card, matching the pattern
        used on standard PLPs if available. At minimum, surface the average score (e.g. ★ 4.6 · 2,847
        reviews) beneath the product name. If the underlying data is already available in the product
        feed, this is a card template config change.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="No bestseller rank or 'why this?' signal on cards"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="no-bestseller-badge"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Cards carry no visual indicator that distinguishes this page from any standard PLP. There are
        no rank badges (#1, #2…), no "Best Seller" labels, no "trending" or "popular" chips — nothing
        on the card face to reinforce that these are the community's top picks. The page brand-hub slug
        and H1 are the only signals that this is a curated selection.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-best-sellers-2026-06-04/product-card-desktop.png" alt="Product card with no bestseller indicator" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users who land via search or social won't see the page heading before the grid. Even those who
        do read the H1 get no per-product signal that individual items are especially well-regarded.
        The strongest conversion cue on a bestseller page — "this specific product is #1" — is completely
        missing. This is particularly damaging for cross-category products (e.g. running shoes alongside
        protein bars) where users need a reason to trust an unfamiliar product.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add a "Best Seller" badge to the card image overlay, using the existing badge component if
        available. Consider positional rank for the top 10 results (e.g. "#1 Best Seller") to drive
        urgency on the highest-converting cards. Design spec required before engineering can implement.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="QUICK BUY missing brand signature mint ring"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="quick-buy-no-mint-ring"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The QUICK BUY button on product cards uses the primary dark-teal fill
        (<code>oklch(0.3162…)</code> / approx <code>#003942</code>) and a 32px border radius — the
        primary CTA treatment — but has no mint (<code>#94E5B5</code>) outer ring. Computed styles
        confirm: <code>box-shadow: none; outline: none</code>. The mint ring is the brand's defined
        signature for the add-to-basket action and is specified in the design system.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The mint ring is a deliberate brand differentiator that visually flags the add-to-bag action
        across all Myprotein touchpoints. Its absence on the listing-page CTA creates inconsistency
        with the PDP experience and may reduce the visual salience of the button — particularly on
        the dark-background card hover state where contrast between the button and its surroundings
        is reduced.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add the mint ring to the QUICK BUY button via the standard box-shadow pattern used on the
        primary add-to-basket button:
        <code>box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px #94E5B5</code> (or the equivalent design token). This is a
        one-line CSS change scoped to the <code>.quick-buy</code> or equivalent selector.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>


    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Mixed category content with no structural separation"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="mixed-category-no-grouping"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The grid intermixes fundamentally different product categories — M&amp;M's chocolate protein
        bars (£19.99), SBD knee sleeves (£74.99), Brooks running shoes (£165), and Saucony trainers
        (£140) — in a single undifferentiated scroll, with no category section headers, no visual
        grouping, and no filtering pre-applied. The page copy acknowledges this ("nutrition,
        accessories, and apparel") but provides no navigational scaffolding to help users orient.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-best-sellers-2026-06-04/above-fold-desktop.png" alt="Above fold showing mixed category products" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A user landing with nutrition intent will scroll past footwear with no map of what's coming.
        The cognitive load of comparing £19.99 bars against £165 trainers in the same row is high,
        and the absence of section grouping makes it harder to filter mentally. This dilutes the page's
        authority — a "Best Sellers" list that jumps randomly between categories feels like an algorithm
        output, not a curated destination.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Either: (a) add sub-section headings within the grid (e.g. "Top Selling Nutrition",
        "Top Selling Equipment", "Top Selling Footwear") to break the mix into scannable sections; or
        (b) default the Product Category filter to a sensible starting state and prompt users to filter
        by department via a tab row above the grid. Requires design spec before engineering work.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Filter label truncated — 'Product Ca...' on desktop"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="filter-label-truncated"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The Product Category filter label is visibly truncated to "Product Ca..." in the filter bar at
        1440px viewport width. This is the same systematic issue observed on the Men's Clothing PLP
        (finding <code>filter-labels-truncated</code>). The filter button has insufficient width to
        accommodate the full label, and no ellipsis or tooltip exposes the hidden text.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-best-sellers-2026-06-04/filters-desktop.png" alt="Filter bar showing truncated Product Ca... label" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users cannot identify what the third filter controls without clicking it. On a cross-category
        page like Best Sellers, the Product Category filter is one of the most important controls —
        it's how users narrow to their relevant department. Truncating its label reduces discoverability
        and use, which means more users scroll a mixed-category grid rather than filtering to their
        actual intent.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Allow filter buttons to grow to fit their label text (min-width approach), or use abbreviated
        but intelligible labels: "Category" instead of "Product Category". This is the same fix needed
        across all PLPs where this pattern is used.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="QUICK BUY button design token violations"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="quick-buy-token-violations"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The QUICK BUY button has three computed style deviations from the design system:
        (1) <code>font-size: 16px</code> — buttons should be <code>14px Bold</code> per spec;
        (2) <code>text-transform: uppercase</code> — the design system does not use all-caps on
        buttons; text should be sentence or title case;
        (3) <code>border-radius: 32px</code> — 32px is the primary CTA radius. A card-level
        quick-add action is a secondary button and should use <code>9999px</code> per the
        secondary button spec.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Uppercase button labels test poorly for legibility at small sizes, and applying the primary
        CTA radius to a secondary action creates visual ambiguity in the button hierarchy. The
        combined effect makes QUICK BUY appear to be the same weight as a primary "Add to Basket"
        button, which dilutes the distinction between browsing and committing actions.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the quick-buy button component: set <code>font-size: 14px</code>, remove
        <code>text-transform: uppercase</code> (use "Quick Buy" in title case), and set
        <code>border-radius: 9999px</code>. These are CSS-only changes in the shared quick-buy
        component.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="'Read More' expander shows negligible additional copy — SEO pattern harming UX"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="read-more-seo-copy"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Directly below the H1, a short paragraph of intro copy is followed by a "Read More"
        hyperlink. Clicking it reveals only a sentence or two of additional text — the expanded
        state adds very little meaningful content. This pattern is a common SEO technique for
        placing keyword-rich copy on a category page without visually cluttering the grid, but
        the implementation here creates a jarring interaction: users click expecting a useful
        expansion and receive almost nothing in return. Additionally, the trigger is marked up as
        an <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> tag rather than a <code>&lt;button&gt;</code>, which is
        semantically incorrect for a toggle action that does not navigate.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The "Read More" interaction sets an expectation it doesn't fulfil — users who click it lose
        trust in the page's responsiveness. The pattern also consumes prime above-fold real estate
        (between the H1 and the filter bar) with low-conversion copy. On mobile this gap is even more
        costly as it pushes the product grid further below the fold. The incorrect use of
        <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> instead of <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> also means keyboard and
        screen reader users get the wrong affordance and no <code>aria-expanded</code> state.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Remove the "Read More" toggle entirely. The amount of additional copy it reveals is too
        small to justify the interaction — show the full text inline or remove the category
        description from this position altogether. If any SEO copy is required above the fold,
        keep it to a single short sentence with no toggle. The filter bar and product grid should
        follow directly below the H1.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Promo banner duplicated in DOM and potentially off-context"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="promo-banner-duplicate"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The promotional message "FREE MODE SPORT BATH SALTS | WHEN YOU SPEND £20+ ON BRANDHUB"
        appears twice in the DOM — two separate elements rendering identical text. Additionally,
        this offer may not apply to all 133 products on the page (e.g. high-value Brooks running
        shoes at £165 are from a third-party brand and may be excluded from the BrandHub promotion).
        No qualifying conditions are surfaced.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Duplicate DOM renders waste bandwidth and may cause screen reader double-reads. More
        critically, if the promotional threshold or eligibility rules are not met, a user who adds
        a non-qualifying product will be confused or disappointed — a trust-breaking experience
        close to the add-to-bag moment.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Remove the duplicate render (one element should be set to <code>display: none</code> or
        removed from markup). Clarify the offer terms with a "T&amp;Cs apply" link or an asterisk,
        and confirm whether the promotion applies to all brands on the page or only Myprotein own-brand.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Sort button doesn't surface current sort order"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="sort-no-current-value"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The Sort dropdown button displays the static label "Sort" with no indication of the currently
        applied sort order. On a Best Sellers page the implied default is "Best Selling" — but this is
        not confirmed to the user. If they have previously applied a different sort (e.g. Price: Low
        to High), the label still reads "Sort" with no way to tell.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users cannot tell whether results are sorted by bestselling rank, popularity, recency, or
        something else. This is a minor friction point but on a page where the ranking order is the
        entire proposition, it is worth surfacing. It also means users who've changed the sort have
        no feedback that their selection persists.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the Sort button to display the active sort value: e.g. "Sort: Best Selling" or
        "Sort: Price ↑". Default to "Best Selling" for this page. This is a JS state-binding
        change in the sort component.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Filter chip border-radius is off-token (5px)"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="filter-chip-border-radius"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Filter dropdown buttons have a computed <code>border-radius: 5px</code>. The design system
        specifies valid border-radius values of 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 56, or 9999px. 5px is not a
        valid token and indicates a hardcoded or miscalculated value. Chips and selector elements
        should use <code>8px</code>.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Minor visual inconsistency with the rest of the design system. Low conversion impact but adds
        to token drift across the codebase.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Set the filter button <code>border-radius</code> to the <code>--radius-sm</code> token (8px).
        One-line CSS change.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="'Brand Hub' breadcrumb uses internal taxonomy unfamiliar to users"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="brand-hub-breadcrumb"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The breadcrumb reads: Home &gt; Brand Hub &gt; Best Sellers. "Brand Hub" is an internal
        navigation construct that does not correspond to a meaningful category for shoppers. Users
        arriving from external search or ads will have no frame of reference for what "Brand Hub"
        means or what it contains.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Breadcrumbs serve two purposes: wayfinding and SEO. An opaque intermediate node ("Brand Hub")
        weakens both. Users cannot infer what they'd find if they clicked back to "Brand Hub", and
        the term is unlikely to match user mental models or search queries.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Consider whether "Brand Hub" as a navigation concept needs a user-facing label review. If the
        parent section genuinely covers "partner brands", a label like "All Brands" or "Partner Brands"
        would be more descriptive. Requires content/IA decision before implementation.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      Typography is consistent — Figtree is the computed font family throughout and the H1 uses
      correct weight (700). However the H1 at 48px is notably large for a listing page and dominates
      the above-fold area, compressing the product grid. Filter buttons carry a non-token
      <code>border-radius: 5px</code> (should be 8px). The QUICK BUY button has three design token
      violations: <code>font-size: 16px</code> (spec: 14px), <code>text-transform: uppercase</code>
      (spec: title case), and <code>border-radius: 32px</code> (secondary buttons spec: 9999px).
      Most critically, the QUICK BUY button is missing the brand signature mint ring
      (<code>#94E5B5</code> box-shadow) that all add-to-basket CTAs are required to carry.
      No incorrect accent colour usage was observed elsewhere on the page.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      Product card images have descriptive alt text (e.g. "M&amp;M's Chocolate HiProtein Bar | 12 x 51g")
      — no empty or missing alt attributes were found on product images. The wishlist heart buttons
      on cards appear to be SVG-icon-only with no visible text — these should carry an
      <code>aria-label</code> (e.g. "Add to wishlist") to be operable by screen reader users; this
      was not confirmed in inspection and should be verified. The "Read More" toggle is covered
      as a dedicated finding (<code>read-more-seo-copy</code>). Colour contrast on the
      QUICK BUY button (white text on dark teal) comfortably meets WCAG AA at its computed size.
      The filter bar is marked with an <code>h2</code> ("Filters") which aids screen reader navigation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      The Best Sellers page has the right ingredients for a high-converting destination — a clear
      community-trust angle, a Quick Buy CTA on every card, and a broad cross-category range —
      but each of these advantages is undermined. The community-trust angle is asserted in copy
      but not demonstrated on the cards (no ratings, no badges). The Quick Buy CTA lacks the brand
      mint ring and has token violations that reduce its visual authority. And the cross-category
      breadth is a strength only if users can navigate it, which requires category grouping or
      filtering guidance that is currently absent. The most urgent fix is restoring social proof
      (ratings + bestseller badges) to the card level — this alone could materially lift
      click-through and add-to-bag rates from the grid.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>Add star ratings and review count to product cards — surface the community social proof the page promises.</li>
      <li>Add mint ring to QUICK BUY button — one-line CSS fix, restores brand CTA signature.</li>
      <li>Add "Best Seller" badge to card image overlay — design spec needed, then engineering implementation.</li>
      <li>Fix QUICK BUY token violations — font size (16→14px), remove uppercase, border-radius (32→9999px).</li>
      <li>Fix filter label truncation — use "Category" instead of "Product Category" or allow buttons to expand.</li>
      <li>Remove duplicate promo banner DOM render and clarify offer eligibility.</li>
      <li>Remove the Read More toggle — the additional copy is too thin to justify the interaction; show inline or remove entirely.</li>
      <li>Introduce category section grouping or a department tab strip above the grid.</li>
      <li>Surface active sort value in the Sort button label.</li>
      <li>Fix filter chip border-radius to 8px token value.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .findings-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .recommendations { padding-left: 20px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .recommendations li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }
</style>
